<TITLE> Stocks, dollar rally after central bank moves </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, March 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - World stocks and the dollar rallied on Tuesday while safe-haven government bonds fell after the world's central banks unveiled joint action to inject liquidity into financial markets. The action to ease market strains, the first since December, involved the US Federal Reserve, the Bank of England, the Swiss National Bank, the European Central Bank and the Bank of Canada. After the announcement the FTSEurofirst 300 index showed gains of 1.7 percent from Monday, while MSCI main world equity index extended gains to 0.7 percent. The index earlier hit its weakest since mid-January. U.S. stock futures were up more than 1.5 percent, indicating a sharply higher open on Wall Street later. The dollar rose nearly a full yen to 102.90 while the euro's gains were trimmed to $1.5386. The June Bund future fell 0.6 percent on the day. Inter-euro zone government bond spreads narrowed after the announcements. The central bank's coordinated move followed the Federal Reserve's new measures on Friday to inject $200 billion of liquidity into markets
